<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-09-08T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-09-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="69" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d69">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">701.6311/147½</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Wilson</persName> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-09-08">
                                    <hi rend="italic">8 September, 1915</hi>.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: I have no doubt that
                            the memorandum handed you by Ambassador Dumba has made the same
                            impression on you that it has made on me. I see no alternative but to
                            follow the course we decided on yesterday. And I think it would be well
                            to apprise Dumba and the press of what that course is to-day, unless <pb facs="0151" n="83" xml:id="pg_83"/> there seems to you to be an
                            impropriety in mentioning it before our communication has reached the
                            Foreign Office in Vienna.</p>
                        <p>Faithfully Yours,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>W. W.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>